Yes, multi-model chaining is Ray Serve's sweet spot:

```python
from ray import serve

@serve.deployment
class TextClassifier:
    def predict(self, text): ...

@serve.deployment
class EntityExtractor:
    def extract(self, text, category): ...

@serve.deployment
class ImageGenerator:
    def generate(self, prompt): ...

@serve.deployment
class Pipeline:
    def __init__(self, classifier, extractor, generator):
        self.classifier = classifier
        self.extractor = extractor
        self.generator = generator

    async def __call__(self, request):
        text = request.json()["text"]
        category = await self.classifier.predict.remote(text)
        entities = await self.extractor.extract.remote(text, category)
        image = await self.generator.generate.remote(entities)
        return {"category": category, "entities": entities, "image": image}
```

Each model scales independently. If image generation is the bottleneck, scale just that deployment. Ray handles load balancing, health checks, and rolling updates.

Deploy on a Ray cluster (KubeRay on K8s) for production. Each model can have different resource requirements (CPU for text, GPU for image gen).
